Juvenal belonged to the middle class Any expres sions in his writings that seem to imply that he was of low rank (as 1. 101 ; 4. 983 8. 44-46) evidently mean no more than that he was connected with the client class and not with the wealthy aristocracy.· He had a house in the city (ιι. 1903 12. 87), an ancestral estate (6. 57) at Aquinum, and a farm at Tibur (11. 6 5) from which his table at Rome was well supplied ( 11. 65-76). Though he lived frugally (11. 131-148), he does not anywhere imply that he had not enough to satisiy his wants, or that, in his later years at least, he was not contented with what he possessed. More- over, he could not have held high civil and priestly office in his native Aquinum il he had not had, for a country town, a large income.1
